arian argues that these poets exaggerated the posture of the downtrodden lover, adapting the rhetoric of powerless desire to forge a new "countersovereignty" from within the heart of vulnerability-a potentially revolutionary position through which to challenge cultural, religious, and political authority. Creating a secular equivalent to the martyr, early modern sonneteers crafted a voice that was both critical and unstoppable because it suffered.Love's Wounds tracks the development of the countersovereign voice from Francesco Petrarca to Maurice Scève, Joachim du Bellay, Théodore-Agrippa d'Aubigné, Edmund Spenser, and William Shakespeare. Through interdisciplinary and transnational analyses, Nazarian reads early modern sonnets as sites of contestation and collaboration and rewrites the relationship between early modern literary forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aEuropean poetryyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and statezEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aLove poetry, EuropeanxHistory and criticism. 0aViolence in literature. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package 2017z978311062534908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/